Local engagement as a countermeasure against populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered resounding electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former president Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar in the Western world everywhere.
The leadership of once-dominant parties oscillates between denial and despair, while populists fish among their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and disparage their supporters as "pitiful," as Hillary Clinton did just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too frightened in the face of the populist tidal wave to launch a counter-offensive.
But neither denial nor self-satisfaction will dissolve the entrenched political situation.
The progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the true issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, worsening environmental crises, increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the avant-garde.
Today they stand alone in the forest and wonder where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed off course.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and government politics has widened into a chasm.
In most western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
But by the time the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national head of government had yet implemented tax cuts based on residency.
Due to this policy, now 1% of France's GDP is primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the questioners became the basis for Macron's presidential election campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment long before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct against women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
Back then, Macron's attitude made him the target of his opponents' jokes; however, the laughter died down quickly with the onset of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
You have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections where activists distribute flyers and cheer for the candidates at intervals.
This was less about cynicism and more about a symptom of an approach that understands democracy as a marketplace, consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, it is the sole purpose of a party to seize and retain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had several advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological edge over less established competitors, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups who could mobilize people to the polls, organize protests, and initiate petitions.
But this model no longer fits.
The citizens refuse to be mere consumers of state policy these days.
Together with higher education levels, new demands for participation emerged.
The voters want to be treated as political actors under their own right and not as pawns in someone else's game.
Moreover, governments are no longer the sole providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we had to learn during the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges of today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions through national governments alone.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures on sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the entry barriers for political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the placeholder bonus and entrenched support networks.
Someone who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well does not need an old-century party apparatus.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should lie on concrete measures and not just on the elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed with people on-site.
At La République En Marche!, we refer to this as local citizen projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems and thereby strengthening the communities.
One should consider such projects today as indispensable supplements to state policy.
In the future, the ability of a party to offer attractive pathways for political and communal engagement will be crucial for its attractiveness.
And by continuously demonstrating their reform policy "live" every day, the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what has to be said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Reestablishing the connection to the concerns of voters goes hand in hand with adapting the party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive policy on the ground.
